# Quality and Security

- Review changes for behavioral regressions, broken anchors, inaccessible controls, missing loading/error states, and responsive layout issues.
- Security-sensitive work includes form submission, API routes, external integrations, dependency updates, and any user input handling.
- Never hardcode secrets, tokens, credentials, private URLs, or production keys. Use environment variables and document required values.
- Do not log personal data from lead forms. Keep error messages helpful without leaking internals.
- For forms, validate required fields, consent, spam protection, and failure states before wiring production submission.
- For external links and embeds, use trusted sources, `rel="noopener noreferrer"` for new tabs, and avoid raw user HTML.
- If a critical or high-confidence security issue appears, stop feature work, report it, and fix it before continuing.
- Code review output should lead with real risks by severity, not style preferences.
